IN THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA
In The Supreme Court

	
		
			
				n the Matter of John A. Pincelli,Â Respondent.
			
		
	


Opinion No. 26400
Submitted October 30, 2007 - Filed December 10, 2007Â Â  

PUBLIC REPRIMAND


	
		
			
				Lesley M.
  Coggiola, Disciplinary Counsel, of Columbia, for Office of Disciplinary
  Counsel.
				J.
  Steedley Bogan, of Columbia, for respondent. 
			
		
	


PER CURIAM:Â  The Office of Disciplinary Counsel
  (ODC) and respondent have entered into an Agreement for Discipline by Consent
  pursuant to Rule 21, RLDE, Rule 413, SCACR, in which respondent admits
  misconduct and agrees to either an admonition or a public reprimand.Â  We accept
  the agreement and issue a public reprimand.Â  The facts, as set forth in the
  agreement, are as follows.
FACTS
In the spring of 2003, respondent created
  an entity known as â€œSandlapper Legal Services, LLCâ€ (Sandlapper) which operated
  out of respondentâ€™s law firm offices under his supervision and direction. While
  Sandlapper was described as a â€œclosing coordination company,â€ respondent agrees
  that, due to the services it provided, Sandlapper was, in fact, a law firm. Â Â 
From 2003 through 2005, Sandlapper
  coordinated closings of approximately 3,000 home equity refinancing loans.[1]Â 
  Sandlapper had approximately fifty (50) South Carolina-licensed attorneys at
  various locations throughout the state to attend closings and serve as closing
  attorneys as contemplated by the directives set out in State v. Buyers
    Services Co., Inc., 292 S.C. 426, 357 S.E.2d 15 (1987), and Doe v. Condon 351 S.C. 158, 568 S.E.2d 356 (2002).[2]Â 
  Respondent represents that the closing attorneys complied with the first three
  closing steps set forth in Doe v. Condon, id., however, Sandlapperâ€™s
  and the closing attorneysâ€™ involvement in the closings ended after the documents
  were executed and turned over to the lender.Â  Instead, Sandlapper and its
  closings attorneys gave lenders written instructions explaining how the lender
  should record the mortgage and any other closings documents.Â   
In March 2004, respondent contacted
  Robert Wilcox, Esquire, and sought his advice as to Sandapperâ€™s procedures.Â 
  Mr. Wilcox provided respondent with a written opinion which advised, in part,
  â€œlawyerâ€™s involvement or active supervision is required also at earlier stages
  of the title search and the preparation of loan documents and at the later
  stages of recordation and disbursement.â€Â  Thereafter, respondent reformed
  Sandlapperâ€™s closing practices to address Mr. Wilcoxâ€™s recommendations, except
  that respondent continued to allow lenders to record their own mortgages through
  reliance on the written instructions provided by Sandlapper. Â In summary, no
  attorney supervised the recordation of the mortgages or other legal documents.[3]Â   
In mitigation, ODC is unaware of any
  damages to clients or lenders as a result of respondentâ€™s misconduct.Â  Further,
  ODC recognizes that lenders were most at risk from respondentâ€™s misconduct yet,
  according to respondent, lenders preferred to record their own mortgages
  without attorney involvement.Â  However, respondent acknowledges that lenders
  cannot authorize variances to Court directives and that errors made in
  recordation by non-attorney supervised lenders might injure subsequent
  assignees of the mortgages.Â   
Respondent warrants that he will make
  every effort toward complying with each and every requirement for the closing
  of real estate transactions as promulgated by the Court.Â  Respondent has fully
  cooperated with ODC in seeking to expeditiously conclude this matter.Â   
LAW
Respondent admits that by his misconduct
  he has violated the following provisions of the Rules of Professional Conduct,
  Rule 407, SCACR:Â  Rule 1.1 (lawyer shall provide competent representation); Rule
  5.5 (lawyer shall not assist non-lawyer in unauthorized practice of law); and Rule
  8.4(a) (it is professional misconduct for lawyer to violate the Rules of
  Professional Conduct).Â  Respondent acknowledges that his misconduct constitutes
  grounds for discipline under the Rules for Lawyer Disciplinary Enforcement,
  Rule 413, SCACR, specifically Rule 7(a)(1) (it shall be ground for discipline
  for lawyer to violate Rules of Professional Conduct), Rule 7(a)(3) (it shall be
  ground for discipline for lawyer to willfully violate a valid order of the
  Supreme Court); and Rule 7(a)(6) (it shall be ground for discipline for lawyer
  to violate oath of office).
CONCLUSION
We find that respondentâ€™s misconduct
  warrants a public reprimand.Â  Accordingly, we accept the Agreement for
  Discipline by Consent and publicly reprimand respondent for his misconduct.
PUBLIC REPRIMAND.
TOAL, C.J., MOORE, WALLER, PLEICONES
  and BEATTY, JJ., concur.

[1] No purchase money mortgages transactions were
  closed by or under the supervision of Sandlapper.Â   
[2] In 2003, the Court withdrew Doe v. Condon, id., and filed the substitute opinion of Doe v. McMaster, 355
  S.C. 306, 585 S.E.2d 773 (2003).Â   
[3] Further, the lenders made their own disbursements at the closings without any
  supervision from an attorney in violation of Doe Law Firm v. Richardson,
  371 S.C. 14, 585 S.E.2d 773 (2006).Â  In Doe Law Firm, the Court held
  that â€œthe disbursement of funds in the context of residential real estate loan
  closings cannot and should not be separated from the [closing] process as a
  wholeâ€ and, therefore, concluded a lawyer should oversee this step in the
  closing process.Â  Id. S.C. at 18, S.E.2d at 868.Â  The Court delayed the
  effective date of the decision until January 22, 2007, to provide time for
  businesses to adjust their practices to conform to the new rule.Â   





